Cab Calloway was an incredible singer, composer, entertainer and dancer. He pioneered many things but his wide variety of talent shadows his innovations in dancing.

I studied Minnie the Moocher along with other of his slow blues soundies. This step would have probably been inspired by shuffles or "fans" in blues dancing but Calloway really puts a personal twist to it and makes it look like he's floating 

The technique is to slightly lift your toe off the ground to get an illusion your foot is floating. Be sure to switch up the rhythm, by accelerating or slowing down. And lastly, use your whole body in the movement, swaying your hips and shoulders.

Here are 6 training for a spiral roll:

1. Roll backward while lifting your legs, then switch legs as you come down.
2. Extend one leg back while pushing the floor. Roll in reverse to come back. 
3. Roll with one leg up while placing your elbows on the floor.
4. Now lightly kick your legs as you roll down. And then stand up naturally.
5. Place your feet against the wall and lift your back. Return down by placing your hands and feet on the wall. Take care of your neck.

With learning, the world becomes more colorful, and the more colorful it gets, the greater my drive to discover new potential nuances it might hold.

Knowledge and skill expand perception, understanding, and sensitivity to layers of the world that would otherwise remain hidden. This is why learning excites me. This is why I practice. All the rest are welcome side effects, but they are not what keeps me on the edge of my seat, ready to leap up at any moment and explore.

Keep learning, keep exploring, and watch the world transform as you constantly grow and change.

Middle Splits and elastic bands.

They go hand in hand just like blood, sweat and tears!
Bands can help you warm up, they can help you train your body to become more resilient to injuries and they can help you build muscles.

There is a difference between a functional core and a pretty 6 pack core.

Most functional cores come with a 6 pack alongside them but not all show off cores are strong and stable. When working on my abs I always try to get as close to the real thing as possible. The question that I like to ask first is what do we actually need the core muscles for? We need them to stabilize our movements and to connect the upper with the lower body. 

Depending on your precise discipline and level your core will have to work a certain way. Most of the time core strength is not the limiting factor. In many cases the lacking point is core coordination or in other words, the ability to engage the core muscles correctly.

This mind muscle connection needs to be trained as well!

Work on gymnastics inspired core stability drills to get a stronger, smarter and more efficient mid section. 
Get better at your movements, protect your spine from injuries and look better at the beach!
